Note for self-grading: you did not have to use inline R code when summarizing the variables. I used it below so that you have an example of how it can be used.

  • species
    • The type of penguin species.
    • R variable type: factor
    • Variable type: nominal
    • Summary: There are are three penguin species types included in the dataset: Adelie (n = 152), Chinstrap (n = 168), and Gentoo (n = 124).
  • island
    • The name of the island the penguins were on.
    • R variable type: factor
    • Variable type: nominal
    • Summary: The penguins data were collected from three different islands: Biscoe (n = 168), Dream (n = 124), and Torgersen (n = 52).
  • bill_length_mm
    • Penguin bill lengths, measured in mm.
    • R variable type: numeric
    • Variable type: continuous
    • Summary: Bill lengths varied from 32.1 mm to 59.6 mm. The average bill length was 43.9 mm with standard deviation 5.5 mm. There were 2 missing values.
  • bill_depth_mm
    • Penguin bill depths, measured in mm.
    • R variable type: numeric
    • Variable type: continuous
    • Summary: Bill depths varied from 13.1 mm to 21.5 mm. The average bill depths was 17.2 mm with standard deviation 2 mm. There were 2 missing values.
  • flipper_length_mm
    • Penguin flipper lengths, measured in mm.
    • R variable type: integer
    • Variable type: discrete (although continuous is acceptable as well)
    • Summary: Flipper lengths varied from 172 mm to 231 mm. The average flipper length was 200.9 mm with standard deviation 14.1 mm. There were 2 missing values.
  • body_mass_g
    • Penguin body masses (or weights), measured in grams.
    • R variable type: integer
    • Variable type: discrete (although continuous is acceptable as well)
    • Summary: Body masses varied from 2700 mm to 6300 mm. The average body mass was 4201.8 mm with standard deviation 802 mm. There were 2 missing values.
  • sex
    • The sex of the penguins.
    • R variable type: factor
    • Variable type: nominal
    • Summary: Data was collected on 165 female and 168 male penguins, in addition to 11 penguins with missing values for sex.
  • year
    • The years the data were collected on the penguins
    • R variable type: integer
    • Variable type: discrete
    • Summary: The penguins data were collected in the years 2007-2009, with roughly the same amount of data from each year.

Data viz: what story are the data telling us?

Scatterplots

Bill length (y-axis) vs. the bill depth (x-axis)

Note: we usually say y-variable vs. x-variable when referring to a scatterplot, which is opposite of thinking about (x,y).

  1. Make a scatterplot of the bill length (y-axis) vs. the bill depth (x-axis).
    • Include some level of transparency of the points.
    • Label the axes with descriptive “nice looking” names that are not the original variable names.
    • Add a title to the plot.
ggplot(data = penguins, 
       aes(x = bill_depth_mm, 
           y = bill_length_mm)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = .3) +
  labs(x = "Bill depth (mm)",
       y = "Bill length (mm)",
       title = "Penguin bill lengths vs. bill depths") 
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  1. Is the linear relationship between these variables best described as being weak, moderate, or strong? Also, is it positive, negative, or neither?

There is not a strong linear relationship between the variable. It’s a weak negative relationship.
Since the relationship is so weak it’s actually difficult to tell if it would be negative or positive. Thus it’s acceptable to say neither or positive instead of negative.

Going deeper with flippers

Let’s explore the distributions of flipper lengths by sex and species.

  1. Make a figure with density plots to compare the distribution shapes by sex. What does this plot tell you both about the shapes and comparing the values between groups?
ggplot(data = penguins, 
       aes(x = flipper_length_mm, 
           fill = sex)) + 
  geom_density(alpha = .3) 
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

The distributions of flipper lengths are bimodal for both male and female penguins (plus for those penguins with missing values for sex). The two peaks for female penguins are slightly two the left of the peaks for male penguins, indicating that female penguins tend to have slightly shorter flippers. However, the two distinct peaks within each sex tells us that the overall bimodal distribution of flipper lengths is due to some variable other than sex, such as possibly species.

Color coding bill length (y-axis) vs. the bill depth (x-axis)

  1. Create two new scatterplots, where one color codes the dots by island and the other by species. 
ggplot(data = penguins, 
       aes(x = bill_depth_mm, 
           y = bill_length_mm, 
           color = species)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = .5) # you were not required to include alpha
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(data = penguins, 
       aes(x = bill_depth_mm, 
           y = bill_length_mm, 
           color = island)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = .5)  # you were not required to include alpha
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  1. Is the relationship between bill length and depth stronger within islands or within species? Describe how you came to this conclusion. Again, assume that you are talking to someone that doesn’t see the plot.

The relationship between bill length and depth is stronger within species than within islands. We can see three almost distinct colored clusters of points for the three different species. Gentoo penguins tend to have smaller bill depths and larger bill lengths, Adelie penguins tend to have larger bill depths and smaller bill lengths, and Chinstrap penguins tend to have both larger bill depths and larger bill lengths. For all three species, we see a positive moderate association between bill length and depth.

In contrast, the plot color-coded by island shows much overlap of islands in the cluster of larger bill depths and smaller bill lengths. Thus Biscoe island penguins are split across two clusters, leading to a weak negative relationship between bill length and depth. Dream island penguins are one larger cluster with no clear positive or negative relationship. The Torgersen island penguins have the strongest relationship between bill length and depth amongst the three islands, which is moderate positive.

Species vs. island?

  1. Take another look at the two color-coded scatterplots. Based on these scatterplots, which species tend to live on which islands?

Adelie penguins live on all three islands, Chinstrap penguins live on Dream, and Gentoo penguins live on Biscoe.

Back to flipper lengths…

  1. Make a figure with density plots of the flipper lengths to compare the distribution shapes by species. What does this plot tell you both about the shapes and comparing the values between groups?
ggplot(data = penguins, 
       aes(x = flipper_length_mm, 
           fill = species)) + 
  geom_density(alpha = .3) 
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

Within each of the species, the distribution of flipper lengths is approximately symmetric with one mode. From this plot we can see that Gentoo penguins tend to have the longest flippers with a mode around 215 mm. Adelie and Chinstrap penguins have much overlap in their flipper lengths, with Adelie’s mode at about 190 mm being slightly smaller than Chinstrap’s mode at about 197 mm.

  1. Make a figure with density plots of the flipper lengths to compare the distribution shapes by both sex and species. Hint: facet!
ggplot(data = penguins, 
       aes(x = flipper_length_mm, 
           fill = species)) + 
  geom_density(alpha = .3) + 
  facet_grid(rows = vars(sex), cols = vars(species), scales = "free_y")
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

# you didn't have to include the scale = "free_y" part, but it does help to see each of the distribution shapes in greater detail

From these plots we see that the distribution of flipper lengths is fairly symmetric and unimodal for each species-sex combination. Male penguins tend to have their modes at slightly larger values that female penguins.

As noted above, Gentoo penguins tend to have the longest flippers with a mode around 215 mm. Adelie and Chinstrap penguins have much overlap in their flipper lengths, with Adelie’s mode at about 190 mm being slightly smaller than Chinstrap’s mode at about 197 mm.

The penguins with missing sex values are from the Adelie and Gentoo species.

Bargraphs

Let’s now explore the categorical variables.

  1. Make a bargraph for the species. Which species is the most common? Least common?
ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = species)) + 
  geom_bar()

In the penguins dataset, Adelie penguins were the most common and Chinstrap penguins the least common.

  1. Make a bargraph for the islands. Which island is the most common? Least common?
ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = island)) + 
  geom_bar()

In the penguins dataset, Biscoe island penguins were the most common and Torgersen island penguins the least common.

Stacked bargraphs

  1. Make a bargraph for the species stacked by sex. Was sex approximately evenly distributed within each species, or was one sex more common for some or all species?
# Either of the 2 bargraphs work for this question.
# The second makes it a little easier to compare the sex distributions by species though.

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = species, fill = sex)) + 
  geom_bar() 

# or
ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = species, fill = sex)) +

Sex approximately evenly distributed within each species.

  1. Make a bargraph for the islands stacked by species. What does this plot tell us about the species inhabitants of each of the islands?
# Either of the 2 bargraphs work for this question.
ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = island, fill = species)) + 
  geom_bar() 

# or
ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = island, fill = species)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "fill")

From these barplots we see that Biscoe had the most penguins (over 150), with close to 75% Gentoo and the remaining Adelie. Dream island had about 125 penguins, split approximately evenly between Adelies and Chinstraps. Torgersen had the fewest penguins (about 50), which were all Adelies.

  1. Make various bargrpahs (at least two) to explore the year variable. Based on your figures, what is your guess for how the data were collected over time? I.e. were different species and islands targeted in different years, or were they all targeted over time?

Below are some sample plots to explore the year variable.

We can see that penguin data was collected for each of the years from 2007 to 2009. There was a slight increase in the number of penguins data was collected on from year to year, but not much (from about 110 penguins in 2007 to 120 in 2009). The number of penguins data was collected on was about the same from year to year on each of the islands and within each of the species, with small fluctuations.
